<font color="#FF0000">I LOVE DOC SPATZ!!!!</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jul 31 22:36:52 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I love you Doc;<br>
I think your the greatest, for a little commie you're all right.<br>
You do, however remind me of one of Mrs. Mendoza's chickens. She lived next door to my grandfather in Las Cruses, New Mexico (yes, doc it is a state). <br>
Mrs. Mendoza's hen had a new batch of little chicks and I remember seeing the little chicks following the hen where ever she would go. All of them walked in a perfect little column except one little chick. It seemed the little thing was born with two left feet. So, where ever Mrs. Mendozas hen would travel that little chick had a heck of a time trying to keep up, it was always out of step and so most of the time it just kept going around and around in circles. Poor little chick, didn't last long, one of the neighbors cat got him one night. I wished I could have done something for that little chick but when you have two left feet, there's not much you can do.<br><br>
Doc, I'm glad you didn't go to Nam, you probably would have gotten yourself killed. <br>
Heck, if you had gone and if I knew you wouldn't run away, why I would have even let you hold my gun ammo while I shot at the gooks.<br>
I wouldn't let you touch the gun though, even Izzie (the Shoshone Indian) will tell you he had to ask permission before I would allow him to shoot it. Don't know what came over me but one night I did let him shoot it. Of course, it wasn't in combat. I let him shoot a few rounds into the Sung Thu Bon River. He remembered though, when we met for our reunion<br><br>
Did I ever tell you about the time I went up to this Arvin lieutenant in DaNang with a grenade in my hand?<br><br>
Doc, even you would appreciate this one, remember doc, I kept a diary and if you like I'll give you the date and the full name of the Marine I was with. <br>
Dumont had send me to Da Nang for supplies and one of the squads had send a brand new Marine by the name of Welsh along with me. I thought I would impress the kid, sort of show off (some of that macho, stuff) and so I took along the fake grenade I mentioned in one of the earlier threads. <br>
When we got to DaNang before we picked up our supplies I approached a well-dressed uniformed ARVIN lieutenant (actually ARVN, Army of the Republic of Vietnam, South Vietnamese regular soldiers, they were suppose to be friendlies).<br>
He was in his mid twenties and stood tall compared to the others gathered around him.  He was doing most of the talking and turned to greet us as we approached.  <br>
I smiled and he acknowledged it. I then took the fake grenade that was hanging from my flak jacket and pulled the pin in front of the ARVN. <br>
Welsh standing to my right became wide eyed.  I extended my arm with the grenade in it to within a foot of the ARVN's chest.  No one moved.  We stood there silent staring at each other for a few seconds while others all around us begin to back off. <br>
The ARVN lieutenant then slowly reached up and without taking his eyes off me removed a grenade from his cartridge belt.  He pulled the grenade up to chest level as I had done. Then he also pulled the pin and extended his arm out to within a foot of my chest.  <br>
Mine was fake, his was real. We stood like that for about two to three of the longest seconds in my life.  I then nodded, smiled and then slowly reinserted the safety pin back into the little hole that held the lever. <br>
I was hoping that he wasn't seeing how badly my hand was shaking. I didn't notice if his hand was shaking as he replaced the pin his grenade.  We then bowed at each other, smiled and backed off.  <br>
As I walked away my knees became weak, they almost buckled under me from the drain of adrenaline, and I almost fell. I quickly looked down at the road and managed to pretend that I had stumbled on something, so that Welsh wouldn't know.   That was the last time I used that fake grenade. Welsh the boot Marine never knew the grenade was fake and I never bothered to tell him.<br><br>
Ah! you probably didn't appreciate it, too much macho stuff in it. I'll look through my book and try and find a story for you that's not so gung ho.<br>

